<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-12-03T15:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-12-03T15:00:00-05:00" n="498" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d498">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/718: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-12-03T15:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">December 3,
                                        1927—3 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>396. Your 1044, November 29, 11 a.m. Department considers that tax
                            referred to by Consul General Shanghai is a violation of treaty when
                            collected on American goods re-exported from one open port to another or
                            shipped to the interior under transit pass. As regards question of
                            protest see Department’s telegram No. 270, July 1, 5 p.m.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
